<strong>Lesson 11 – Breaking Down a Cover Letter</strong>

&nbsp;

Remember, a cover letter is used to:
<ul>
 	<li>Introduce yourself.</li>
 	<li>Invite an employer to read your resume.</li>
 	<li>Highlight some of the most important qualities from your resume.</li>
 	<li>Request an interview.</li>
</ul>
&nbsp;

<strong><u>Writing the Body Paragraphs</u></strong>

The body of a cover letter can seem intimidating! If you are stuck, breaking the letter down into small pieces can help.

Here is an easy, step-by-step guide on what to include in your body paragraphs.

<em>These are the “bones” of each paragraph, but you may need to add more description to make your sentences flow together.</em>
_________________________________________________________________________________
<strong>State your intention (applying) and to what job:</strong>

<em>Example: I am interested in applying for the office assistant position at Work Inc.</em>

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<em><strong> </strong></em>

<strong>Where did you find out about this job opening?</strong>

<em>Example: I saw your advertisement on Craigslist on November 5, 2013.</em>

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<em><strong> </strong></em>

<strong>Optional: Why are you interested in this job, or this field?</strong>

<em>Example: I am looking to develop my office skills so that I can eventually work as an office manager.</em>

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<em><strong> </strong></em>

<strong>Optional: What information will be in the rest of the letter? Describe the other body paragraphs.</strong>

<em>Example: I am very qualified for this job, and have attached a resume highlighting my skills.</em>

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Great! Now, you can use the sentences you wrote above to put together a strong first paragraph!

____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<em>Before you move on, read your sentences out loud to your partner, get their feedback, and make edits!</em>
_________________________________________________________________________________
Look at the job advertisement and think about what you know already about the job. <strong>What <strong>qualities</strong> is the employer looking for?</strong> (Either hard or soft skills.)
<ol>
 	<li><em><strong>Example: Good Customer Service</strong></em></li>
 	<li><em>_____________________________________</em></li>
 	<li><em>_____________________________________ </em></li>
 	<li><em>_____________________________________</em></li>
</ol>
<strong>Now look at your resume. Are there any items, activities, or experiences from your resume that would show that you have one of the qualities listed above?</strong>

<em>Example:</em>

<em>Experience from resume: <strong>Volunteer at soup kitchen</strong></em>

<em>Quality: <strong>Good customer service</strong></em>

Experience from resume: ­_______________________________________

Quality: ______________________________________________

&nbsp;

Experience from resume: ­_______________________________________

Quality: ______________________________________________

&nbsp;

Experience from resume: ­_______________________________________

Quality: ______________________________________________

<strong>Good! Now, select the <strong>two qualities</strong> of the job that you think you possess most strongly. Write a sentence or two for each that includes:</strong>
<ul>
 	<li>What skill you have.</li>
 	<li>What experience you have using or learning that skill.</li>
 	<li><strong>How you can apply that skill to this new job.</strong></li>
</ul>
<em>Example:</em>

<em>“I spent two years volunteering at a soup kitchen, where I learned how to be polite to many people while serving them. This knowledge will carry over into a job as a waiter, since I will be very pleasant and efficient during a dinner rush.”</em>

<em><u> </u></em>

<u>Now you do it! Write about the first quality here:</u>

_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________<em>___________________________________________________________________</em>

<strong>Now, pick a different quality and do the same thing:</strong>

____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<em>Good! You can either combine these to make one paragraph, or make each one into its own paragraph. If you have two paragraphs, add another support to each one by highlighting another skill from your resume. </em>

<em> </em>

<strong>Copy your sentences from the previous page here to make your second paragraph!</strong>

<em><u>___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________</u></em>

<em>Before you move on, read your sentences out loud to your partner, get their feedback, and make edits!</em>

________________________________________________________________________________
<strong>Remind the employer that you are interested in an interview (politely!).</strong>

<em>Example: I am interested in an interview so I can speak with you more about the position.</em>

____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<strong>Tell them that you will follow up, and say when and how you will (by phone, email, etc.). <strong>OR </strong>you can provide your own contact information.</strong>

<em>Example: I look forward to hearing from you. You can reach me at 617-222-2222, and I will follow up by email in one week.</em>

_________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

<strong>Finally, don’t forget to thank them for taking the time to read your letter!</strong>

<em>Example: Thank you for your time and consideration.</em>

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

